snippet.title: Current | Introduction to electrical engineering | Electrical engineering | Khan Academy

snippet.description:
The positive sign for current corresponds to the direction a positive charge would move. In metal wires, current is carried by negatively charged electrons. The positive current arrow points opposite the direction the electrons move. This has been the sign convention for 270 years, ever since Ben Franklin name electric charges with + and - signs, 150 years before the discovery of the electron.

snippet.description: The "operational amplifier" has two differential inputs and very high gain. Willy describes the symbol and properties of an op-amp. Op-amps are the backbone of analog circuit design.
snippet.title: What is an operational amplifier?

snippet.description: An op-amp can be used to amplify a voltage. The gain is determined by the ratio of the resistors in the circuit.
snippet.title: Non-inverting op-amp circuit

snippet.description: Feedback is the design technique where a portion of the amplifier output "feeds back" to the input of the amplifier. The overall effect creates a very stable gain factor determined by resistor ratios.
snippet.title: Feedback

snippet.description: The inverting op-amp circuit is the most commonly used configuration. We analyze the inverting configuration, doing all the algebra from first principles.
snippet.title: Inverting op-amp circuit

snippet.description: The idea of a "virtual ground" makes some simplifying assumptions and give us a really elegant and simple way to look at op-amp circuits.
snippet.title: Virtual ground

snippet.description: Using the "virtual ground", we reexamine the inverting op-amp circuit and find a solution much quicker. We apply the virtual ground method to a unity-gain buffer (amplifier with gain = 1).
snippet.title: Inverting and unity-gain op-amp with virtual ground

snippet.description: This op-amp circuit performs the sum of two input voltages. It is a way to do analog arithmetic on signals.
snippet.title: Summing op-amp circuit

snippet.description: The inductor-capacitor (LC) circuit is the place where sinewaves are born. We talk about how this circuit works by tracking the movement of an initial charge we placed on the capacitor.
snippet.title: LC natural response intuition 1

snippet.description: We can predict the shape of voltage and current in an LC circuit by tracking the motion of charge as it flows back and forth.
snippet.title: LC natural response intuition 2

snippet.description: We begin the derivation of the natural response of the LC circuit, by modeling it with a 2nd-order differential equation.
snippet.title: LC natural response derivation 1

snippet.description: Starting from the differential equation, we come up with a proposed exponential solution and plug it into the equation. This gives us a characteristic equation. A "natural frequency" emerges.
snippet.title: LC natural response derivation 2

snippet.description: We use Euler's Formula to change our complex exponential solution into a solution expressed in terms of sines and cosines.
snippet.title: LC natural response derivation 3

snippet.description: In this final step of the derivation, we find two initial conditions and use them to come up with a sinusoidal solution for the LC natural response.
snippet.title: LC natural response derivation 4

snippet.description: We solve the voltage and current if an example LC circuit with given values for L and C, and an initial charge on the capacitor.
snippet.title: LC natural response example

snippet.description: Solving circuits with differential equations is hard. If we limit ourselves to sinusoidal input signals, a whole new method of AC analysis emerges.
snippet.title: AC analysis intro 1

snippet.description: Here's a preview of how AC analysis is going to work. To get ready we need to review some of the ideas from trig and complex numbers.
snippet.title: AC analysis intro 2

snippet.description: A quick review of some ideas from trigonometry that will help us with AC analysis. The definitions of sine, cosine, and tangent, circles, degrees, radians.
snippet.title: Trigonometry review

snippet.description: Sine and cosine can be generated by projecting the tip of a vector onto the y-axis and x-axis as the vector rotates about the origin.
snippet.title: Sine and Cosine come from circles

snippet.description: If we introduce time as the argument to the sine function, we get a sine wave.
snippet.title: Sine of time

snippet.description: One way to generate sine and cosine is to track the motion of a rotating vector.
snippet.title: Sine and cosine from rotating vector

snippet.description: Sine and cosine look similar, except they are out of phase. When we talk about sine and cosine as a function of time, the difference is called "lead" or "lag".
snippet.title: Lead Lag

snippet.description: Complex numbers can be represented three ways on the complex plane: cartesian coordinates, radius and angle, and exponential form.
snippet.title: Complex numbers

snippet.description: Multiplying any real or complex number by the imaginary unit j corresponds to a rotation. This is the key feature of j that makes it such a useful number.
snippet.title: Multiplying by j is rotation

snippet.description: Euler's formula relates the complex exponential to the cosine and sine functions. This formula is the most important tool in AC analysis. It is why electrical engineers need to understand complex numbers.
snippet.title: Eulers formula

snippet.description: A closer look at the complex exponential term in Euler's Formula. We see that it represents a complex number, a distance of 1 from the origin of the complex plane.
snippet.title: Eulers formula magnitude

snippet.description: When we put time up in the exponent of a complex exponential, the complex number it represent rotates in a circle on the complex plane. You can think of it as a spinning number!
snippet.title: Complex exponentials spin

snippet.description: A sine wave emerges from Euler's Formula. Music, no narration. Animated with d3.js.
snippet.title: Eulers sine wave

snippet.description:
A cosine wave emerges from Euler's Formula. Music, no narration. Created with d3.js

The background music is NirvanaVEVO by Chris Zabriskie. It is licensed under a Creative Commons Attribution license (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/)

Source: http://chriszabriskie.com/uvp/, Artist: http://chriszabriskie.com/
snippet.title: Euler's cosine wave

snippet.description: The concept of negative frequency is perplexing, but it makes sense when you think about rotating complex exponentials
snippet.title: Negative frequency

snippet.description: The general notion of the ratio of a sinusoidal voltage to a sinusoidal current is called "impedance". We derive the impedance of a resistor, inductor, and capacitor. The impedance of the inductor and capacitor has a term for frequency, so the impedance of these components depends on frequency.
snippet.title: Impedance

snippet.description: A sneak preview of AC analysis: We break a sinusoidal input voltage into two complex exponentials. Using superposition, we recover the complex output signals and reassemble them into a real sinusoidal output voltage.
snippet.title: AC analysis superposition

snippet.description: Multiplying a real or complex number by the imaginary unit j corresponds to a rotation by +90 degrees. This is the key feature of j that makes it such a useful number.
snippet.title: Complex rotation

snippet.description: The impedance of inductors and capacitors depends on frequency. We discover the origin of the phrase "a capacitor looks like a short at high frequency."
snippet.title: Impedance vs frequency

snippet.description: We look at the inductor i-v equations in derivative and integral form.
snippet.title: Inductor equations

snippet.description: We notice how important it is to give inductor current a place to flow.
snippet.title: Inductor kickback 1 of 2

snippet.description: We give the inductor's kickback current a path to flow by adding a diode
snippet.title: Inductor kickback 2 of 2

snippet.description: Introducing the diode as a circuit element. A diode conducts current in one direction but not the other.
snippet.title: Diode

snippet.description: We solve a diode circuit graphically by plotting a diode i-v curve and resistor to find the intersection. Graphical solution methods are a common way to work with non-linear components like diodes.
snippet.title: Diode graphical solution

snippet.description: Fourier Series introduction
snippet.title: Fourier Series introduction

snippet.description: Definite integrals of sin(mx) and cos(mx)
snippet.title: Definite integrals of sin(mx) and cos(mx)

snippet.description: Definite integral of sine and cosine product
snippet.title: Definite integral of sine and cosine product

snippet.description: Definite integrals of product of sines
snippet.title: Definite integrals of product of sines

snippet.description: Definite integral of the product of cosines. The integral of cos(mt) * cos(nt) = 0, except for the special case when m = n. When m = n, the integral evaluates to pi.
snippet.title: Integral of product of cosines

snippet.description: Formula for first term in Fourier Series
snippet.title: Formula for first term in Fourier Series

snippet.description: Formula for cosine coefficients in a Fourier Series
snippet.title: Fourier series coefficients for cosine terms

snippet.description: Formula for Fourier coeffients for sine
snippet.title: Fourier coefficients for sine terms

snippet.description: Finding Fourier coefficients for square wave
snippet.title: Finding Fourier coefficients for square wave

snippet.description: Visualizing the Fourier expansion of square wave. A square wave can be approximated by adding odd harmonics of a sine wave.
snippet.title: Visualizing Fourier expansion of square wave

snippet.description: Remember the relationship between current and voltage in an inductor and capacitor with the help of ELI the ICE man.
snippet.title: ELI the ICE man

snippet.description: Demonstration that Kirchhoff's voltage law applies in the frequency domain. The voltage phase offsets around a loop sum to zero.
snippet.title: KVL in the frequency domain

snippet.description: Impedance of two elements in series is a complex number. Impedance terminology: reactance, susceptance, admittance.
snippet.title: Impedance of simple networks
